FreeRTOS is a real time kernel on top of which embedded applications can be build to meet their hard time requirements. The kernel decides which thread should be executed by examining the priority of each thread. This feature is implemented in its source code using a large number of lists. Several API's are invoked on these particular lists. However, as per the set protocol, certain violations are observed in the source code that leads to several bugs in the implementation of FreeRTOS. In this project, we performed a static analysis of the source code using CIL and designed and implemented an algorithm to find the possible invocations that violate the protocol. In addition, context mining was performed on the source code to extract all the shared resources followed by a lock set analysis to verify whether there was an access to any of the shared resources without acquiring proper locks.
